<br>
I work in guest service everyday and have done so for the past 4 years.  Of course our motto (and my personal one as well) is the guest always comes first.  <br>
<br>
No one in my department would even think twice about answering a ringing phone (our business phone, not personal phones) if there was someone there, in person who needed to be helped.<br>
<br>
Yet, I find it amazingly rude how people can come up to the counter with a cell phone in hand and point at me trying to halfassedly (is that a word?) indicate what they want, while carrying on a conversation with someone else.  When I try to greet the person with a smile and a hello half the time they just blurt what they want without making eye contact and continue on blabbering to whomever it is on the phone.<br>
<br>
I don't *have* to go out of my way to be nice in my job.  I don't work on commission and my job only requires me to greet and thank our guests.  I am nice because I like to be.  I think something as small as a genuine smile and hello can make someones shopping experience better.  All I ask is that when people come to the counter they at least show a small amount of respect to the people who are there, trying to make things pleasant for them.<br>
<br>
Anyway, that was a bit of topic BUT I guess I should say I think that was *horrible* what the guy at the gas station did.  Cell phone or not, you don't have to be rude to your guests and YOU don't have to be a patron there ever again <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
